04328nam a22007215i 9780691188188DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911881887 a10.1515/97806911881882doi  a(DE-B1597)501819  a(OCoLC)1076478370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBR735b.S67 2008eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh 7aREL0330002bisacsh 7aREL1020002bisacsh04a274/.072231 aSorkin, David, eauthor.14aThe Religious Enlightenment :bProtestants, Jews, and Catholics from London to Vienna /cDavid Sorkin. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJews, Christians, and Muslims from the Ancient to the Modern World00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Maps -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. Brant Broughton, London, Gloucester William Warburton's "Heroic Moderation" -- tCHAPTER TWO. Geneva Jacob Vernet's "Middle Way" -- tCHAPTER THREE. Halle Siegmund Jacob Baumgarten's "Vital Knowledge" -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Berlin Moses Mendelssohn's "Vital Script" -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Vienna- Linz Joseph Eybel's "Reasonable Doctrine" -- tCHAPTER SIX. Toul-Paris-Lyon Adrien Lamourette's "Luminous Side of Faith" -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary -- tIndex  aIn intellectual and political culture today, the Enlightenment is routinely celebrated as the starting point of modernity and secular rationalism, or demonized as the source of a godless liberalism in conflict with religious faith. In The Religious Enlightenment, David Sorkin alters our understanding by showing that the Enlightenment, at its heart, was religious in nature. Sorkin examines the lives and ideas of influential Protestant, Jewish, and Catholic theologians of the Enlightenment, such as William Warburton in England, Moses Mendelssohn in Prussia, and Adrien Lamourette in France, among others. He demonstrates that, in the century before the French Revolution, the major religions of Europe gave rise to movements of renewal and reform that championed such hallmark Enlightenment ideas as reasonableness and natural religion, toleration and natural law. Calvinist enlightened orthodoxy, Jewish Haskalah, and reform Catholicism, to name but three such movements, were influential participants in the eighteenth century's burgeoning public sphere and promoted a new ideal of church-state relations. Sorkin shows how they pioneered a religious Enlightenment that embraced the new science of Copernicus and Newton and the philosophy of Descartes, Locke, and Christian Wolff, uniting reason and revelation to renew faith and piety. This book reveals how Enlightenment theologians refashioned belief as a solution to the dogmatism and intolerance of previous centuries. Read it and you will never view the Enlightenment the same way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aEnlightenmentzEurope. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188188zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188188.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN